message.content: Setting $f(x)=f^{-1}(x)$, we get $2x-5 = f^{-1}(x)$.  To find $f^{-1}(x)$, we can solve $y=2x-5$ for $x$ and switch $x$ and $y$ to get $x=2y-5$.  Therefore, $f^{-1}(x)=2x-5$.  So we have $2x-5=f^{-1}(x) = x$.  This gives $x=\boxed{5}$. Checking, we see that $f(5) = 2(5)-5=5$, as does $f(5)=f^{-1}(5)$.
